"1497":"1497","25 November 1450":"25 November 1450","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1405":"1405","Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Lenthall Sparkes, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Besselsleigh, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bessels Leigh, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baxter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>baxter</i> ‘baker’ (from Old English <i>bæcestre</i> ‘baker’, earlier ‘female baker’, the feminine equivalent of <i>bæcere</i>). Compare   Baker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kempster","meanings":["English: occupational name for a wool or flax comber, MiddleEnglish <i>kem(be)stere</i> (an agent derivative of Old English<i>cemban</i> ‘to comb’). Although this was originally a feminine formof the masculine <i>kembere</i>, by the Middle English period thesuffix <i>-stre</i> had lost its feminine force, and the term was usedto refer to both sexes. Compare   Baxter  ,   Brewster  ,   Dexter  ."]},{"name":"Baker","meanings":["English: occupational name, from Middle English <i>bakere</i>, Old English <i>bæcere</i>, a derivative of <i>bacan</i> ‘to bake’. It may have been used for someone whose special task in the kitchen of a great house or castle was the baking of bread, but since most humbler households did their own baking in the Middle Ages, it may also have referred to the owner of a communal oven used by the whole village. The right to be in charge of this and exact money or loaves in return for its use was in many parts of the country a hereditary feudal privilege. Compare   Miller  . Less often the surname may have been acquired by someone noted for baking particularly fine bread or by a baker of pottery or bricks.","Americanized form (translation into English) of surnames meaning ‘baker’, for example Dutch   Bakker  , German   Becker   and   Beck  , French   Boulanger   and <b>Bélanger</b> (see   Belanger  ), Czech <b>Pekař</b>, Slovak <b>Pekár</b>, and Croatian   Pekar  .","History: Baker was established as an early immigrant surname in Puritan New England. Among others, two men called Remember Baker (father and son) lived at Woodbury, CT, in the early 17th century, and an Alexander Baker arrived in Boston, MA, in 1635."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margery Baxter was born about 1430, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Henry Baxter. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Lenthall. She died in 1479, in her hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"Abt 1430–1479":"umbes 1430–1479","1430–1479":"1430–1479","1425–1450":"1425–1450","1450–1497":"1450–1497","1405–Male":"1405–Surnud","Abt 1450":"umbes 1450","1425":"1425","1479":"1479","Abt 1430":"umbes 1430","1497":"1497","25 November 1450":"25. november 1450","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1405":"1405","Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lenthall Sparkes, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Besselsleigh, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bessels Leigh, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1430–1479":"noin 1430–1479","1430–1479":"1430–1479","1425–1450":"1425–1450","1450–1497":"1450–1497","1405–Male":"1405–Kuollut","Abt 1450":"noin 1450","1425":"1425","1479":"1479","Abt 1430":"noin 1430","1497":"1497","25 November 1450":"25. marraskuuta 1450","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1405":"1405","Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lenthall Spar